(X,d)
A
X
d_A:X\to\mathbb R:x\mapsto\displaystyle\inf_{a\in A} d(x,a)
c\in X
\delta>0.
\exists~\epsilon>0
x\in B(c,\epsilon)\implies |d_A(x)-d_A(c)|<\delta.
\displaystyle\epsilon=\frac{\delta}{2}.
x\in B(c,\epsilon)
a\in A,~|d(x,a)-d(a,c)|\le d(x,c)<\epsilon
-\epsilon<d(x,a)-d(a,c)<\epsilon.
\forall~x\in B(c,\epsilon)
\forall~a\in A,~-\epsilon+d(a,c)<d(x,a)\\\implies -\epsilon+d_A(c)< d(a,x)\\\implies d_A(c)\le d_A(x)+\epsilon\\\implies d_A(c)-d_A(x)\le\epsilon\cdots(1)
\forall~x\in B(c,\epsilon)
\forall~a\in A,~d_A(x)\le d(x,a)<\epsilon+d(a,c)\\\implies d_A(x)-\epsilon<d(a,c)\\\implies d_A(x)-\epsilon\le d_A(c)\\\implies-\epsilon\le d_A(c)- d_A(x)\cdots(2)
|d_A(x)-d_A(c)|\le\epsilon<\delta.
d_A
